title: Athens, Parthenon
text: Walked up the Acropolis late afternoon to marvel at this magnificent ancient structure. Watched the sun filter through the columns. Looks great from afar when lit up at night.

title: Athens, Acropolis
text: Went there first mid morning and the queues were massive so walked all around the base exploring the streets, churches and cafes. Returned late afternoon and there was no queues. Walked to the top and marvelled at the magnificent ruins. Sat down and watched the sun filter through the Parthenon. Left when I thought it was closing time but the staff weren't in any hurry to get people to leave.

title: Sofia, Rotunda Church of St George
text: This church is among the archaeological diggings in the middle of Sofia. Well worth walking through all the diggings and see how people are saving their history.
place: The Rotunda Church of St George

title: Sofia, Saint Nikolas Church
text: Found this while wandering around after visiting the big church. Great golden onions on top of the spires and inside was great for an eastern church. No photos allowed inside as with most orthodox churches.
place: Saint Nikolas Russian Church (Tsurkva Sveta Nikolai)

title: Sofia, St Alexander Nevski Cathedral
text: A truly amazing cathedral and worth every bit of the money 5 lev they ask you to pay if you want to take photos. I cannot believe people won't pay and sneak around taking photos. A member of the staff trying in vain to police this came up and thanked me for paying as he saw the receipt in my hand. One of the church highlights of 3 months in Europe.

title: Bucharesti, National Theatre
text: Was just down the Boulevard from where we were staying. The security guard allowed us to walk around the foyer as it was closed, impressively modern. When we walked past it later a Georgian folk group were giving a performance in front of the statues at the front. Stayed until they finished. They were good, entertaining and I did not understand a word they said but i enjoyed it.

title: Bucharesti, Palaces of Parliament.
text: The main place I wanted to visit in Bucharest as my Romanian friends said it is massive but unfortunately it didn't happen. One day the Palace was closed for some public holiday and the next day the heavens opened up so we did not get off the bus. The building is impressive and so huge. Maybe next time.

title: Bucharest, Parcul Herastrau
text: Got off the HopOn HopOff bus and walked down to the lake then strolled around this beautiful park heading towards the Arc de Triomph, a smaller version of Paris's. Just near the Arc there is an avenue and statue dedicated to Michael Jackson. The park is large, peaceful and uncrowded-Lovely place.

title: Budapest, Heroes Square
text: A great square dedicated to Hungary's past. Take time to marvel at the statues as it is well worth the time spent looking at them. The buildings around the square are also great and there is a castle just across a bridge which is worth a look.

title: Budapest, St Stephens Basilica
text: Another wonderful European basilica. Beautifully decorated inside and a great place to visit when it is raining outside.

title: Budapest, Liberty (Green) Bridge
text: Stayed very close to this magnificent steel bridge. Walked down to it on our first night then went back there the next day and it was open for pedestrians only with performers and dancers putting on entertainment for free. Wonderful weekend use of a vehicular bridge.

title: Budapest, Gellert Hill
text: Took the little train up the hill towards the Citadella then walked up to the top to the big statue. Lovely views of the city from the top especially the river and the bridges. Walked all the way back down to the river.

title: Budapest, Danube (Duna) River
text: The Danube is so huge. Walked along the banks between the Green Bridge and the Chain Bridge, wonderful walk. Took an afternoon cruise down the river and on the way back all the big cruise boats were leaving. Should have gone back to the river at night and done the night cruise but didn't have the time.

title: Budapest, Buda Castle
text: Budapest has so many beautiful historic places to visit. The Castle is one of them. A good idea is to take your time and appreciate the beauty of this place.

title: Kilcunda, Bass Coast Rail Trail
text: Stayed again at Kilcunda caravan park and decided to walk towards Anderson this time as I had already walked to Wonthaggi and back several times. As it was such a good walk kept going all the way to Woolamai race course then back. Over 20kms of easy walking.

title: Budapest, St Gellert Thermal Baths
text: Just went to look inside at the building like many others. Great looking building and you can see quite a lot of its interesting features. Worth the time, but maybe next time go swimming.
place: St. Gellért Thermal Bath and Swimming Pool

title: Zagreb, Cathedral of the Assumption
text: Zagreb is no different to other European capitals having an inspiring cathedral that has great stained glass windows. Outside the church has great ornate features and like most buildings has ongoing maintenance to keep it great.

title: Zagreb, St Marks Church
text: Church wasn't open but the outside views of the roof is a great spectacle as is the buildings around St Mark's Square

title: Ljubljana, Tromostovje
text: An amazing structure. When I saw it I stood in awe as I thought what a novel way of doing it. Haven't seen anything like it anywhere but its purpose is achieved beautifully. Ljubljana is a hidden joy with lots of amazing things. Even has a kangaroo fountain for us Aussies.

title: Ljubljana, Pizzeria Ljubljanski
text: Choosing where to eat in Ljubljana is hard as there are so many along the river to choose from. This pizzeria was great. Good food and good drinks in a great outdoor setting.

title: Ljubljana, River Canal
text: Travelled along the canal in a timber boat. The captain kept people informed about what we were passing and was really informative. As the day was warm the cruise was really pleasant.

title: Ljubljana, Old Town
text: One of the hidden gems of Europe. Reminds me of Brugge. Walking around the old town on either side of the river is fantastic and full of cafes and bars.

title: Ljubljana, Castle
text: An amazing castle that towers over the beautiful city of Ljubljana. Actually went on a tower which was very informative interspersed with actors playing period parts. Great time. Then walked around exploring. Really great castle.

title: Bratislava, Cumil statue.
text: Found this statue of a man coming out of a manhole while walking around the Old Town. Amazing piece of art.

title: Bratislava, GoodDay Cafe
text: One of the many cafes on the edge of of the Old Town. Had a really good meal, good service but the only drawback is they didn't have local beer.

title: Bratislava, Bratislava Castle
text: This castle will be great when the restoration is complete. Will love to go back when it is completed. It burnt down 200 years ago and was left o decay. Luckily restoration started about 70 years ago during the Communist era. When they fit out all the rooms like other palaces it will be stunning. Even now well worth the visit.

title: Bratislava, UFO Observation Deck
text: A wonderful place for a viewing platform. The main support for a bridge. A lift gets you to the top where you can view the river and city and there is a restaurant where you can sit around admiring the views.

title: Bratislava, Devin Castle
text: Took the boat down to this castle that Napoleon destroyed over 200 years ago. Great views of the Danube from the top. A great place to spend the day.

title: Warsaw, Marie Curie Monument
text: Found this statue along the river when walking around the Old Town. A wonderful inspirational woman. It always amazes me what you can find walking around cities.

title: Warsaw, Lazienka Palace
text: What a magnificent palace and gardens in Warsaw. The palace straddles an artificial lake for a wonderful effect and the other out-buildings in the park are also worth a good look. Spent all day there.

title: Warsaw, Palace of Culture & Science Viewing platform
text: A good old communist era building which looks like a mini Empire State Building that has a viewing platform on the 33rd floor. Well worth the small wait to get into the lift. Gives a great view of Warsaw.

title: Warsaw, Old town Observation Terrace
text: A well placed bell tower that you can climb up for magnificent views of Warsaw's Old Town. Well worth the climb.

title: Warsaw, Statue of the Little Insurgent
text: A truly inspirational monument to the children that got caught up in the WW2. It may be small but it was amazing the amount of people looking at it.

title: Warsaw, Uprising Monument
text: A really well done monument to the horror that was the 1944 Warsaw Uprising. Took some time to read about it as we tend in this country to mistake it for the earlier Warsaw Ghetto Uprising.
place: Monument to the Warsaw Uprising Fighters

title: Warsaw, Old Town
text: Walked around Warsaw's Old Town or should I say rebuilt Old Town. I was blown away (sorry the pun) about how they restored Warsaw after the WW2. Amazing

title: Vilnius, Gate of Dawn
text: Walked up the staircase to the top where a service was taking place with signs requesting not to photograph. I didn't but a lot of people obviously are very ignorant. Although I could not understand it I enjoyed the service. Afterwards wandered through the church at the bottom.

title: Vilnius, Church of St Rafael
text: This church was undergoing outside renovation but they still allow people to visit. Wonderful church that will be stunning when finished.
place: Church of St. Rafael the Archangel

title: Vilnius, Mergeles Marijos Dievo Motinos Church
text: Saw this striking church while walking around Vilnius. Didn't realise it was across the river. Was worth the walk.

title: Vilnius, Castle Hill.
text: Took the lift up to the castle rather than walking. The view from the castle were great and even better from the tower. The castle grounds are being restored and from the top of the tower you can see the progress and in a year or two it will look amazing.

title: Vilnius, Cathedral
text: Another beautiful cathedral right in the middle of Vilnius. Outside looks impressive but inside it is just devine.

title: Vilnius, Gediminas Tower
text: Saw this amazing tower and fort from our BnB and had to visit it as it would have great views of Vilnius. It did.

title: Vilnius, Bell Tower
text: Saw this wonderful looking tower on edge of Cathedral square. Climbed up it just as it started to rain. Great views when the rain stopped.

title: Vilnius, Cathedral Square
text: A great square to wander around and look at things. Decided to climb up that amazing tower and was not disappointed.

title: Vilnius Old Town
text: Another great Old Town centre in Europe. Unspoiled by re-development. Walked from rail/bus station to the river. Great walk and well worth getting lost at times.

title: Riga, Hog Cafe
text: Went in there for a look at all the Harley Davidson memoriabilia and also a beer. Great little cafe and the staff openly welcome sightseers.

title: Riga, TGI Friday's
text: A great burger restaurant to hide from the rain. Was surprised with the great taste of the burger I had and the staff were very welcoming.

title: Riga, Aussie Pub
text: Found this pub when walking around Riga. Went in for a beer and to look at the Australiana. Only Aussie beer was Coopers in a bottle so I had a local beer from the tap. Wasn't disappointed. The staff love Aussies dropping in.

title: Riga, Freedom Monument
text: A stunning monument in the middle of Riga. A good photo opportunity along the broad avenue leading to it and is spectacular up close.

title: Riga, Ghetto
text: Walked around the Riga Ghetto and wondered why the area had not been restored like other areas. Was told the reason. Still a great area to walk around and look at buildings.
place: Riga Ghetto and Latvian Holocaust Museum

title: Riga, House of the Blackheads
text: What a marvelous ornate building. Looks great from the outside and inside is no different. It is great how people rebuild.

title: Riga, Old City
text: The best thing about European cities is that preserve or rebuild their city centres. Riga has a lovely one that you can walk around, marvel at the old buildings, sit in a cafe, eat lovely meals, drink local produced drinks and watch the world go by.

title: Riga, Central Market
text: Walked through the outside stalls on our way to our BnB then came back for as the fruit and vegies looked so good. Came back next day for more and went inside for the meat and fish. Everything so cheap, fresh and so tasty. History of the buildings and how and where they came from so interesting.

title: Tallinn, Lux Express
text: Traveling around Europe by train wherever possible but had to get a bus to Riga. Checked on line for buses but decided to book in person. Wonderful pleasant staff that were very helpful, so much so that used them in Riga to get to Vilnius and then to Warsaw. Wish they went from Sofia to Athens as the bus-line we used was terrible.

title: Tallinn, Estonian History Museum
text: In a really beautiful building is this wonderful museum highlighting Estonia's Independence from Russia, both times. Well worth time spent viewing their struggle.
place: Maarjamae Palace Estonian History Museum (Maarjamae Loss)

title: Tallinn, Kiek in de Kok and underground passage
text: Started off the walk around the walls by going through this underground walk beneath the walls. Wonderful walk especially on a warm day.
place: Kiek in de Kok and Bastion Passages Museum

title: Tallinn, Trofe Restaurant
text: While walking around the Old Town found this great friendly restaurant. Sat outside enjoying the warm weather. We had great meals, cool drinks and wonderful service from staff.

title: Tallinn, Kadriorg Palace
text: Another great European styled palace with fantastic gardens surrounding it. Well worth a visit to admire how the wealthy lived in the past.

title: Tallinn, Great Guild Hall
text: Another museum in Tallinn worth visiting. Great to see the trading history of the town and the stories with it.

title: Tallinn, Town Walls
text: A really great walk along the walls of Tallin and into turrets that have themes. Walk not difficult and well worth the experience.

title: Tallinn, Seaplane Harbour Museum
text: Spent most of one day in this wonderful museum. Walked around the seaplane hanger that was full of watercraft, naval guns and a submarine. Also watched a great movie called "Sex and the Sea". Than walked out around the harbour area of the museum that had great exhibits including an old icebreaker. Wonderful museum worth visiting.
